Problem 1: 50 States in the USA

In this problem we will use the state dataset, available as part of the R statistical computing platforms. This data is related to the 50 states of the United States of America. Load the data and use it to answer the following questions.

(a) Describe the data and each variable it contains.

state.abb - Character vector of 2-letter abbreviations for the state names.

state.area - Numeric vector of state areas (in square miles).

state.center - List with components named x and y giving the approximate geographic center of each state in negative longitude and latitude. Alaska and Hawaii are placed just off the West Coast.

state.division - Factor giving state divisions (New England, Middle Atlantic, South Atlantic, East South Central, West South Central, East North Central, West North Central, Mountain, and Pacific).

state.name - Character vector giving the full state names.

state.region - Character vector giving the region of the state, for ex South,West,East,North. state.x77: Matrix with 50 rows and 8 columns giving the following statistics in the respective columns. Population: Population estimate as of July 1, 1975

Income: Per capita income (1974)

Illiteracy: Illiteracy (1970, percent of population)

Life Exp: Life expectancy in years (1969–71)

Murder: Murder and non-negligent manslaughter rate per 100,000 population (1976)

HS Grad: Percent high-school graduates (1970) Frost: Mean number of days with minimum temperature below freezing (1931–1960) in capital or large city Area: Land area in square miles Convert it into a tidy data frame preparing it for analysis.

(b) Murder rate

Suppose you want to explore the relationship between a state’s Murder rate and other characteristics of the state, for example population, illiteracy rate, and more. Begin by examining the bivariate relationships present in the data. Create a series of scatterplot and add a trend line (geom_smooth(method="lm")). What does your analysis suggest might be important variables to consider in building a model to explain variation in murder rates?

For analysing bivariate relationships, I beleive the best method is to use correlation and for this purpose I will be using Pearson’s correaltion coefficient which I found from the source:http://www.sthda.com/english/wiki/correlation-test-between-two-variables-in-r I will be correlating murder to all the other variables present in our data Your code and explanations…

#creating a function to find correlation
#also not choosing the nominal variables
cor_func<- function(x)
{
  cor(state_table$Murder,state_table[,x], use = "pairwise.complete.obs", method = c("pearson"))
}

cor_res<- map_dbl(colnames(state_table[1:8]),cor_func)

cor_table<- tibble("Variable"= colnames(state_table[1:8]),"Correlation factor"=cor_res)

cor_table

From the above tables we see that the 2 variables that are the most correlated are Illiteracy and Life Expectancy which makes sense. Here Illiteracy has a positive correlation and Life Expectancy has a negative correlation.

Life expectancy is obvious because if you have a higher murder rate in a state we will inturn have a lower life expectancy as the average will fall down because of the number of murders.

##Visualizing the correlationship using a smoothening line

ggplot(data= state_table)+ aes(x =state_table$Murder, y = state_table$Illiteracy) + geom_point(color="blue") + geom_smooth(method = "lm") + xlab("Murder Rate") + ylab("Illiteracy Rate") + ggtitle("Correlationship between murder and illiteracy")

ggplot(data= state_table)+ aes(x =state_table$Murder, y = state_table$`Life Exp`) + geom_point(color="blue") + geom_smooth(method = "lm") + xlab("Murder Rate") + ylab("Life Expectaancy") + ggtitle("Correlationship between murder and Life expectancy")

From our analysis we prove that Illiteracy has a positive bivariate correlation with murder as the slope of the smoohtening line shows and Life Expectancy has a negatice bivariate correlation with murder as the slope of the smoohtening line shows.

Research Question: How is the murder rate related to the population of different states in our dataset.

First I will group the data into 3 categories 1) Lowly population 2) Moderate Population 3) High Population

# cutting the data into 3 groups
population_factor<-cut(state_table$Population,breaks = 3,labels = c("Lowly Population","Moderate Population","High Population"))

state_table<-state_table %>% mutate(population_factor)
state_table
ggplot(data = state_table) + aes(x = state_table$Murder,y = state_table$Population) + geom_point(color = "firebrick3")+ facet_wrap(~population_factor,ncol=3)

We see from the above analysis that Majority of the states are lowly populated 1) Majority of the lowly populated areas have a low murder rate 2) Although we have very less observations for the moderately populated states we can still say that most of them have high murder rate(<8). 3) Although we have very less observations they are on the higher side.

The dataset we are using contains a record for each crime committed in Seattle, and is partitioned based on the “Beat” in which it occured. To understand the divisions in Seattle, I am explicitly pasting the meaning of three variables which seem important. Explanation for Precint, Sector, and Beats from the Seattle govt. website. . . “Seattle is divided into five geographic areas. Within those areas are the 5 precincts or police stations: North, East, South, West and Southwest. Precinct boundaries were determined through consideration of neighborhood boundaries, geographic and other natural boundaries. Each precinct contains smaller geographic areas called Sectors. There are 17 sectors total in the city. Each of these Sectors are divided into between 3 smaller sections called Beats (i.e. Ocean sector has three beats O1, O2, O3) These are the areas that individual patrol officers are assigned responsibility for.” Apart from variables pertaining to the crime itself, we have information about each Beat’s location and the education levels of the population in that beat. This fact is important as I am going to try and base my hypothesis around this.

Problem 3: Sampling with and without Replacement

In the following situations assume that half of the specified population is wearing a cap and half are not.

Hint: make sure you have read Openintro Statistics (OIS) 3.3 (p 112)

(a) Sampling in a small room

Suppose you’re sampling (uniformly) from a room with 10 people. What is the probability of sampling two persons with cap when sampling with replacement? What is the probability when sampling without replacement?

# with replacement : Can be picked again# Since 5 out of 10 people have cap in the sample. 
#The probability of picking someone with cap is
(5/10)*(5/10)
## [1] 0.25
# without replacement: can not be picked again.# In this case probably for second pick will change,

#since First person with cap who is already picked, can not be picked again.

(5/10)*(4/9)
## [1] 0.2222222
(b) Sampling in a big stadium

Now suppose you’re sampling from a stadium with 10,000 people. What is the probability of sampling two persons with cap when sampling with replacement? What is the probability when sampling without replacement?

#with replacement : Can be picked again
(5000/10000)*(5000/10000)
## [1] 0.25
#without replacement: can not be picked again
(5000/10000)*(4999/9999)
## [1] 0.249975
(c) We often treat individuals who are sampled from a large population as independent. Using your findings from parts (a) and (b), explain whether or not this assumption is reasonable.

1)When we have a small group of 10, there was larger variation in probability of getting two persons with capsin cases of with and without replacement. 2)Although in larger population of 10000, the probablities of getting two persons with capsin both cases of with and without replacement were nearly same.

Concluding it’s an OK assumption to treat indiviuals sampled from a large population as independent for analytical purposes.
